--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. CURRENT SYSTEM ASSESSMENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What the repository actually is (in practice):
  A GitHub profile automation engine whose sole consumer is the GitHub profile
  page at github.com/szmyty. It runs three to four scheduled workflows that
  fetch data from external APIs, render SVG files, and commit the results back
  to the repository. The human-readable README is the only "product"; everything
  else is scaffolding to keep that README looking current.

Where it feels messy or over-engineered:

  a) The repo conflates three distinct concerns in the same flat namespace:
     source content (README, branding), generated artifacts (metrics SVGs,
     profile cards), and operational tooling (workflows, config files). There
     is no clear separation between what a human authors and what a machine
     produces.

  b) profile-summary-card-output/ contains 64 themed subdirectories (320+
     SVG files) for a feature that is only ever displayed in the README as a
     single chosen theme. All 64 themes are committed and versioned even though
     only one or two are actually referenced. This is the single largest source
     of repository noise.

  c) github-metrics.svg lives at the repository root while the other four
     metrics SVGs live under metrics/. This split communicates no intent and
     creates an implicit two-tier output structure that is never explained.

  d) The audits/ directory now contains two distinct types of files: structured
     audit reports (.log) and informal diagnostics documents (.md). Mixing
     these signals that the directory's purpose has not been clearly defined.

  e) The repository markets itself as DX-first but its own setup is opaque:
     no onboarding path, no local development story, and a devcontainer.json
     that does nothing beyond specifying an image name.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. STRUCTURAL ISSUES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Folder structure problems:

  Root level is cluttered. github-metrics.svg, metrics.plugin.16personalities.svg,
  and resume.pdf sit at the root alongside README.md and config files. These are
  logically outputs or assets, not project-root items. A visitor scanning the
  root cannot quickly distinguish source files from generated artifacts.

  profile-summary-card-output/ is misnamed and misplaced. The directory name is
  an implementation artifact (the output path baked into the upstream action)
  not a deliberate design decision. It suggests output, which is correct, but
  the name is too long and too tool-specific to belong at the root.

  metrics/ and github-metrics.svg are logically the same category (generated
  metrics) but live in different locations. The legacy SVG at the root should
  either move into metrics/ or be removed when the four-panel layout fully
  supersedes it.

  metrics.plugin.16personalities.svg is an orphaned file at the root. It is not
  referenced in any workflow output step and not linked from the README. Its
  origin is unclear and it adds unexplained clutter.

  assets/emojis/ contains a single file (zap.png) alongside a .gitkeep. The
  subdirectory level is unnecessary for one file; the emojis/ layer adds
  indirection without benefit.

  branding/ and assets/ serve overlapping purposes. branding/ holds SVG/PNG
  visual assets; assets/ also holds visual assets. The distinction between
  "branding assets" and "other assets" is not documented anywhere and risks
  growing into an inconsistent split.

  docs/ contains architecture.md, secrets.md, and workflows.md, but the
  previous audit reported it as empty (only .gitkeep). Files were added since
  then, but the .gitkeep remains, which is now unnecessary.

Misplaced files or responsibilities:

  audits/metrics-diagnostics.md, audits/metrics-selfhost-diagnostics.md, and
  audits/readme-update-diagnostics.md are informal run notes rather than
  structured reports. They are stored alongside formal audit logs, blurring the
  purpose of the audits/ directory. These should either live in a logs/ or
  scratch/ subdirectory, or not be committed at all.

  resume.pdf belongs to personal branding/assets, not the repository root. Its
  presence at the root makes the directory feel like a miscellaneous dump.

Redundant or unnecessary components:

  64 profile-summary-card themes. The README references one theme. Committing
  all 64 creates 320+ versioned binary SVGs with no practical benefit. Each
  daily run diffs hundreds of SVG files, making git history difficult to read.

  github-metrics.svg (legacy). The four-panel metrics/ layout supersedes this
  file. It is referenced in the README as a "complete" view but duplicates data
  already visible in the four individual panels. Its retention appears to be
  inertia rather than intent.

  metrics.plugin.16personalities.svg. No reference to this file exists in any
  workflow or in the README. It should be removed.

  assets/emojis/.gitkeep. The directory contains a real file; the .gitkeep is
  no longer needed.

  docs/.gitkeep. Same as above; real content files now exist in docs/.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. AUTOMATION DESIGN REVIEW
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

GitHub Actions architecture:

  Five workflows exist: metrics.yml, profile-summary-cards.yml,
  update-readme.yml, lint.yml, and health.yml. Their responsibilities are
  coherent but their designs are inconsistent.

Overlapping responsibilities:

  metrics.yml runs the lowlighter/metrics action five separate times (four
  focused panels plus one legacy SVG). Each invocation repeats the same
  configuration block (timezone, retries, optimize, config_* flags). This is
  DRY-violating YAML: twelve to fifteen identical key-value pairs are
  duplicated across five steps. Any change to shared settings requires five
  edits.

  update-readme.yml and profile-summary-cards.yml both commit generated files
  back to the repository but use slightly different git configuration idioms.
  metrics.yml uses a third variant. Three workflows, three git commit patterns,
  no shared composite action or reusable workflow to enforce consistency.

  health.yml and lint.yml serve similar quality-gate purposes but are separate
  workflows. health.yml checks structural existence of files; lint.yml checks
  formatting. These could reasonably be consolidated into a single "quality"
  workflow with multiple jobs, reducing workflow file count and unifying the
  quality gate concept.

Schedule alignment issues:

  metrics.yml runs at 00:00 UTC.
  update-readme.yml runs at 00:15 UTC.
  profile-summary-cards.yml runs at 00:30 UTC.
  The staggering is correct and avoids the simultaneous-run problem noted in the
  previous audit. This is a strength.

Opportunities to simplify or consolidate:

  The five repeated lowlighter/metrics invocations in metrics.yml should share
  a YAML anchor or, preferably, be extracted into a reusable composite action
  that accepts the filename and plugin flags as inputs. This would halve the
  size of metrics.yml and make plugin configuration changes a single-point edit.

  The git commit/push pattern (configure, add, diff, commit, push) is repeated
  across three workflows. A shared composite action (e.g.,
  .github/actions/commit-and-push) would centralize this logic and ensure all
  workflows use identical commit authorship and message conventions.

  profile-summary-cards.yml checks for the presence of PERSONAL_ACCESS_KEY at
  runtime. This runtime guard is necessary, but the workflow still appears in
  the Actions tab even when it does nothing. Consider using a repository
  variable to advertise whether the feature is enabled, making the workflow's
  intent clearer to readers.

  The update-readme.yml workflow uses jamesgeorge007/github-activity-readme
  pinned to v0.5.0, which is good. However, it does not commit with [skip ci],
  which means a README update push could trigger the metrics workflow on
  master/main push. Verify that the metrics workflow's push trigger does not
  create a re-run loop for README-only pushes.


