6. PROPOSED IMPROVED STRUCTURE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Proposed layout:

  /
  ├── README.md                        (source: only human-authored content)
  ├── CONTRIBUTING.md
  ├── resume.pdf                       (moved from root — consider release asset)
  ├── .github/
  │   ├── dependabot.yml
  │   ├── actions/
  │   │   ├── commit-and-push/         (shared composite action)
  │   │   └── metrics-panel/           (shared metrics generation composite)
  │   └── workflows/
  │       ├── metrics.yml
  │       ├── profile-cards.yml        (renamed from profile-summary-cards.yml)
  │       ├── update-readme.yml
  │       ├── lint.yml
  │       └── health.yml
  ├── assets/
  │   ├── header.svg                   (merged branding/ into assets/)
  │   ├── logo.svg
  │   ├── badges/
  │   └── emojis/
  ├── docs/
  │   ├── architecture.md
  │   ├── workflows.md
  │   └── secrets.md
  ├── generated/
  │   ├── metrics/                     (moved from metrics/ at root)
  │   │   ├── overview.svg
  │   │   ├── github-stats.svg
  │   │   ├── top-languages.svg
  │   │   └── contributions.svg
  │   └── profile-cards/               (renamed, contains only active theme)
  │       └── default/
  └── audits/
      ├── YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM-SS-audit.log
      └── YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM-SS-refactor-audit.log

Why this is better:

  generated/ makes the machine-vs-human boundary explicit and unambiguous.
  Anything under generated/ is created by workflows and should not be manually
  edited. Everything outside generated/ is source content.

  Merging branding/ into assets/ eliminates the overlapping-purpose confusion.
  All static visual assets live in one place.

  Collapsing profile-summary-card-output/ to generated/profile-cards/ with
  only the active theme removes hundreds of committed binary files and makes
  the directory name meaningful rather than tool-specific.

  Moving metrics/ under generated/ removes the root-level SVG clutter while
  keeping files logically grouped.

  .github/actions/ houses shared composite actions that the individual
  workflows call, making the "commit and push" pattern and the "metrics panel
  generation" pattern DRY and centrally maintained.

  Renaming profile-summary-cards.yml to profile-cards.yml is a small
  improvement but signals that names should be chosen by the repository owner,
  not inherited from the upstream tool.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. REFACTOR RECOMMENDATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Establish a generated/ directory and move all workflow outputs into it.
   Update README image paths and workflow output paths accordingly. This is
   the highest-leverage structural change: it immediately clarifies what is
   source vs. output for every reader and contributor.

2. Remove github-metrics.svg (legacy SVG) and its generating step in
   metrics.yml. Update the README to remove the "Complete GitHub Metrics"
   section that references it. The four-panel layout already covers the same
   information more clearly.

3. Limit profile-cards output to one selected theme. Change the card workflow
   to generate only the theme referenced in the README. Delete the 63 unused
   theme directories from the repository. This removes 300+ binary files from
   version history going forward and dramatically reduces noise in daily diffs.

4. Create a shared composite action for the git commit/push pattern. Extract
   the git-configure, git-add, git-diff-check, git-commit, git-push sequence
   into .github/actions/commit-and-push/action.yml. All three generator
   workflows call this composite. One place to fix commit message format,
   authorship, and push behavior.

5. Extract a shared composite action for lowlighter/metrics invocations. The
   five repeated step blocks in metrics.yml share a large set of common inputs.
   A composite action that accepts filename and plugin-specific flags as
   parameters reduces metrics.yml to five compact, readable step blocks.

6. Merge branding/ into assets/ and remove the branding/ directory. Update
   all README image references. The merged directory should use clear
   subdirectories: assets/branding/, assets/emojis/ if needed.

7. Delete orphaned and unused files: metrics.plugin.16personalities.svg,
   assets/emojis/.gitkeep, docs/.gitkeep. These are low-effort removals that
   reduce ambient noise and demonstrate follow-through.

8. Populate the devcontainer.json with practical tooling: Node.js (for
   Prettier and markdownlint), recommended VS Code extensions (already listed
   in .vscode/extensions.json), and a postCreateCommand that installs the
   Prettier and markdownlint CLIs. A working devcontainer makes the DX-first
   claim credible.

9. Add a Makefile (or Taskfile) with targets: lint, fmt, audit, health. These
   targets replicate what CI does, enabling local verification before pushing.
   A single make lint command that mirrors the lint.yml job is the most direct
   local DX improvement possible.

10. Replace placeholder featured project links in the README with real,
    hyperlinked repositories or remove the section entirely. A portfolio that
    references non-existent projects undermines trust with technical visitors.
    This is the highest-visibility credibility gap in the repository today.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The szmyty/szmyty repository is a capable and well-automated GitHub profile
system that has improved meaningfully since its initial audit, but it still
conflates source content with generated artifacts, carries significant binary
bloat from 64 unused profile-card themes, and repeats operational patterns
(git commit, metrics generation) across multiple workflows without shared
abstractions. The proposed direction is to introduce a generated/ directory
to enforce a clean source/output boundary, reduce the profile-card output to
one active theme, extract shared composite actions to eliminate YAML
duplication, and close the gap between the repository's DX-first branding and
its actual local developer experience.


